3. Display the percentage distribution of the data in each year using the pie chart.¶

In [8]:
# Calculate the percentage distribution of data in each year

years = df['year'].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100

# Create a pie chart of the percentage distribution

plt.pie(df.year.value_counts(),autopct="%.1f%%",labels=years.index.astype(str))
plt.title('Percentage Distribution of Data by Year')
plt.show()

5. Plot and understand the relationship between the variables 'numcol' and 'prodval' through scatterplot, and write your findings.¶

In [15]:
# Create a scatter plot of numcol vs. prodval

x=df["numcol"]
y=df["prodvalue"]

plt.scatter(x,y)

plt.xlabel=("numcol")
plt.ylabel=("prodvalue")
plt.title('Number of Colonies vs. Production Value')

plt.show()

# as we can see from the scatter plot that numcol and prod value is co related as when "numcol" is increasing 
# "prodvalue" is also increasing

6. Plot and understand the relationship between categorical variable 'year' and a numerical variable 'prodvalue' through boxplot, and write your findings¶

plt.xlabel('year')
plt.ylabel("prodvalue")
plt.title('Relationship between Year and Prodvalue')

columns=["numcol","yieldpercol","totalprod","prodvalue","stocks","priceperlb"]
